"'''SOS'''" is a song by [[Barbadian people|Barbadian]] recording artist [[Rihanna]] from her second studio album, ''[[A Girl Like Me (Rihanna album)|A Girl Like Me]]'' (2006). It was written by [[J. R. Rotem]], [[Evan "Kidd" Bogart]] and [[Ed Cobb]], with production helmed by Rotem. It was released on March 27, 2006, as the [[Lead single|lead single]] from the album. "SOS" is a [[dance-pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song with elements of [[dance music]], and contains a compositional sample of "[[Tainted Love]]", a song written by Ed Cobb in 1965 and popularised by [[Soft Cell]]. Critical reception of "SOS" was positive, with the majority of [[Music journalism|music critics]] praising the inclusion of the "Tainted Love" sample. Some critics compared "SOS" to Rihanna's debut single, "[[Pon de Replay]]" (''[[Music of the Sun]]'', 2005). 

"SOS" became a commercial success. In the United States, it topped the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart for three consecutive weeks, becoming Rihanna's first number one single on the chart. "SOS" peaked at number one on the US [[Hot Dance Club Play]] songs chart and [[Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs)|Pop Songs]] chart. "SOS" was certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] for shipments of over 1,000,000 copies. In Europe, on many charts across the continent, peaking at number two in Belgium (Flanders), Finland and the United Kingdom. Three music videos were shot for "SOS"; aside from the official music video, directed by [[Chris Applebaum]], promotional campaign videos were shot for lingerie brand [[Agent Provocateur (lingerie)|Agent Provocateur]] and [[Nike Inc.|Nike]]. "SOS" was performed live at the 2006 [[MTV_EMA#2006|MTV EMA]] awards in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]].<ref name="MTVEMA">{{cite web|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1651672/rihanna-ema-show-chance-discover-new-music.jhtml|title=Rihanna Says EMA Show Is A Chance To Discover New Music|publisher=[[MTV]]. [[Viacom]]|date=2010-11-07|accessdate=2012-01-08}}</ref> "SOS" was included on the [[set list]] of the [[Last Girl on Earth Tour]] (2010-11), in which Rihanna performed 'rock-influenced' version.<ref name="LGOE">{{cite web|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1645689/rihanna-dazzles-at-soldout-new-york-show.jhtml|title=Rihanna Dazzles At Sold-Out New York Show|publisher=MTV. Viacom|date=2008-08-13|accessdate=2012-01-08}}</ref>

==Background and conception==
[[File:JR Rotem LF.JPG|thumb|right|upright=0.80|[[J. R. Rotem]] (''pictured'') co-wrote and produced "SOS", and came up with the idea of sampling "[[Tainted Love]]", written by [[Ed Cobb]] in 1965.]]
"SOS" was written by [[J. R. Rotem]], [[E. Kidd Bogart|Evan "Kidd" Bogart]] and [[Ed Cobb]], with production helmed by Rotem.<ref name="Notes"/> The song was recorded at Bartmitzvah Hall Studios, [[Century City]], [[California]], and Loft Recording Studios, [[Bronxville]], [[New York]].<ref name="Notes"/> "SOS" contains a [[Sampling (music)|sample]] of "[[Tainted Love]]", written by [[Ed Cobb]] in 1965, and popularised by [[Soft Cell]].<ref name="Notes"/> In an interview with [[HitQuarters]], Rotem explained the song's conception, saying "I heard 'Tainted Love' and wanted to take the bass line and update it with a new swing. When I gave the track to Evan [Bogart], the 80s feeling was already in the track."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_JR_Rotem_Interview.html |title=Interview With JR Rotem|publisher=[[HitQuarters]]|date=2010-04-04 |accessdate=2011-40-08}}</ref> Rotem was asked how he felt about working with singers who became successful international recording artists after he had worked with them in an interview with William E. Ketchum for HipHopDX in May 2011, and referred to Rihanna and writing "SOS" in his response, saying:

{{quote|I did [Rihanna]'s song <U+201C>[SOS],<U+201D> and it wasn't her first song, but it was her first number one. Since then, she's obviously one of the biggest stars in the world. But I never look at it like that's because of me or something like that. I just look at it like it was amazing to have worked with her at that time, and I would like to work with her again.<ref name="HipHopDX">{{cite web|last=Ketchum|first=William E.|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/interviews/id.1698/title.producers-corner-jr-rotem|title=Producer's Corner: JR Rotem|publisher=HipHopDX|date=2011-05-13|accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref>}}

Originally, "SOS" was intended to be given to and recorded by former [[Def Jam Recordings]] label mate [[Christina Milian]], for her third studio album, ''[[So Amazin']]'' (2006), but Milian turned down the song and former Def Jam CEO and chairman [[LA Reid]] offered the song to Rihanna instead.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lelinwalla|first=Mark|url=http://www.vibe.com/news/news_headlines/2006/06/island_def_jam_drops_christina_milian/|title=Island Def Jam Drops Christina Milian : VIBE.com|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|publisher=[[InterMedia Partners]]|date=2006-06-12|accessdate=2009-08-13}}</ref> After the release of ''So Amazin''', Milian was dropped from Def Jam due to poor album sales.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moss|first=Corey|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1537803/christina-milian-looking-fresh-start.jhtml|title=Christina Milian Looks For Fresh Start After Being Dumped By Island Def Jam|publisher=MTV. Viacom|date=2006-08-03|accessdate=2012-01-01-}}</ref>

==Production and mixing==
The [[Backing vocalist|background vocals]] in the song were compressed using a compressor program called [[Waves Audio|Waves ''Renaissance Compressor'']], which was used in order to create an enhanced polished effect.<ref name="PhilTanSoundOnSound">{{cite web|url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/feb07/articles/insidetrack_0207.htm|title=Secrets Of The Mix Engineers: Phil Tan|work=[[Sound on Sound]]|accessdate=2012-01-03}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Sound on Sound]]'', [[Audio engineering|mixing engineer]] [[Phil Tan]], who carried out the [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|audio mixing]] on "SOS", explained that he compressed the background vocals because "SOS" is a "high energy track", and he wanted the vocals to compliment it.<ref name="PhilTanSoundOnSound"/> Tan also noted that the background vocals were pitch shifted to increase tonal quality and create an enhanced effect during the chorus.<ref name="PhilTanSoundOnSound"/> The pitch shifting consisted of making the left vocals [[Flat (music)|flat]] and the right vocals [[Sharp (music)|sharp]], with varying degrees of delay, and later mixing them together.<ref name="PhilTanSoundOnSound"/> When asked about the production of the [[Lead vocalist|lead vocals]], Tan explained that {{" '}}SOS' Is a pounding type of song, and the lyrics are a cry for help, so the vocals need to be 'in your face', almost aggressive," and said that he wanted the vocals to remain constant.<ref name="PhilTanSoundOnSound"/> As with the background vocals, the lead vocals were compressed using the Waves ''Renaissance Compressor''.<ref name="PhilTanSoundOnSound"/> Tan continued to note that the lack of [[Reverberation|reverb]] included on "SOS" was largely due to the fact that being an uptempo song, there was not a lot of room left to add anything else.<ref name="PhilTanSoundOnSound"/> Tan explained the production process of sampling "Tainted Love", as well as the changes which were made:

{{quote|This song uses a stereo two-bar loop from Soft Cell's song 'Tainted Love' as its basis. JR played the additional parts with a combination of soft and hardware synths. There were probably 30 to 40 tracks in total. JR tends to give you [Pro Tools] Sessions that have a clear direction: there's not much guesswork. I didn't change or add much, just a bass drum and taking out the loop a couple of times for additional breaks. There was never any doubt that it was going to be a clubby song, so it had to be very immediate and hard-hitting.<ref name="PhilTanSoundOnSound"/>}}

==Composition==
{{listen|filename=Rihanna - SOS.ogg|title="SOS"
|description=A 23 second audio sample of Rihanna singing the chorus of "SOS". The sample includes the [[Synthesizer|synth]] [[Riff#Riff|riffs]] and [[Beat (music)|machine beats]] instrumental,<ref name="RollingStoneGenre"/> as well as the layered and compressed vocals.<ref name="PhilTanSoundOnSound"/>
|pos=right}}

"SOS" is a [[Up-tempo#U|up-tempo]]<ref name="PhilTanSoundOnSound"/> [[dance-pop]] and [[contemporary R&B]] song,<ref name="AllMusicGenre">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/unfaithfulsos-r845387|title=Unfaithful/SOS  - Rihanna|publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[All Media Guide]] ([[Rovi Corporation|Rovi]])|accessdate=2012-01-02}}</ref> that draws influence from [[dance music]].<ref name="USATodayGenre">{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/reviews/2006-04-24-listen-up_x.htm|title=Springsteen revs up Seeger|work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|accessdate=2012-01-02}}</ref> The song includes [[Synthesizer|synth]] [[Riff#Riff|riffs]] and [[Beat (music)|machine beats]] as part of its instrumental.<ref name="RollingStoneGenre">{{cite news|last=Walters|first=Barry|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/a-girl-like-me-20060526|title=Rihanna - A Girl Like Me|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner]]|accessdate=2012-01-02}}</ref> The lyrical content of the song is based around the theme of a "boy meets girl" scenario; Quentin B. Huff of Popmatters provided a synopsis of the lyrical content, writing that "SOS" is a "classic tale of girl-sees-boy, girl-falls-head-over-heels, girl-dreams-of-boy-so-much-she-loses-herself, girl-sings-catchy-pop-song-about-boy, girl-sells-lots-of-records."<ref name="Popmatters"/> "SOS" contains a sped up sample<ref name="VibeGoogleBooks">{{cite news|url=http://books.google.mu/books?id=6CYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA160&dq=&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Rihanna - A Girl Like Me|work=Vibe|publisher=InterMedia Partners|accessdate=2012-01-03}}</ref> of "[[Tainted Love]]", which was originally written by [[Ed Cobb]] in 1965 and popularised by [[England|English]] [[synthpop]] duo [[Soft Cell]], when they released their cover version in 1981.<ref name="Top40SingleReview"/><ref name="ContactMusic"/>

The use of the 'Tainted Love' sample was well-received by critics. Ruth Jamieson of ''[[The Observer]]'' commented that the sample was an "outrageously hooky Soft Cell rhythm."<ref>{{cite news|last=Jamieson|first=Ruth|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2006/apr/23/34|title=Rihanna, A Girl Like Me|work=[[The Observer]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=2006-04-22|accessdate=2012-01-03}}</ref> Jazzily Bass of [[Contactmusic.com]] complimented the inclusion of the "Tainted Love" sample, describing "SOS" as "superbly infectious."<ref name="ContactMusic">{{cite web|last=Bass|first=Jazzily|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/pages/rihannax05x06x06|title=Rihanna <U+2013> A Girl Like Me <U+2013> Album Review|publisher=[[Contactmusic.com]]|accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref> Bass continued to praise the song for not making the sample too obvious, writing "I was accepting it to sound like every other song that has sampled the hook."<ref name="ContactMusic"/> Jake C. Taylor of [[Sputnikmusic]] noted that although "SOS" was "yet another exploitation of [[Soft Cell]]<U+2019>s 1981 rendition of Ed Cobb's 'Tainted Love,{{' "}} he concluded that Rihanna's version was one of the better ones to be composed, writing, "Rihanna's is one of the better ones. Why? Because it<U+2019>s not just a bastardised version trying to claim success of the exact same song structure."<ref name="SputnikMusic">{{cite web|last=Taylor|first=Jake C.|url=http://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/26029/Rihanna-A-Girl-Like-Me/|date=2008-06-19|title=Rihanna <U+2013> A Girl Like Me (album review)|publisher=[[Sputnikmusic]]|accessdate=2010-09-11}}</ref> Kelefah Sanneh of ''[[The New York Times]]'' described the inclusion the "Tainted Love" sample as being "brazen" and "astute."<ref name="NYTimes">{{cite news|last=Sanneh|first=Kelefah|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9403E2DD123FF937A15757C0A9609C8B63|title=Critic's Choice: New CD's|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, Jr.]]|date=2006-04-26|accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref>

==Release==
"SOS" was first released in France on March 27, 2006, as a physical [[maxi single]].<ref name="FrenchRelease">{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.fr/Sos-Rihanna/dp/B000F1ILRI/ref=sr_1_3?ie=UTF8&qid=1325466489&sr=8-3|title=Rihanna - SOS|publisher=Amazon.fr|date=2006-03-27|accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref> The maxi single included both the [[radio edit]] and [[instrumental]] versions of "SOS", as well as the album track "[[Break It Off]]", which features Jamaican reggae singer [[Sean Paul]].<ref name="FrenchRelease"/> In Australia, the song was released to [[Music download|download digitally]] through the [[iTunes Store]] on April 3, 2006, with non-single track "Let Me" featuring as the [[A-side and B-side|B-side]].<ref name="AustralianRelease">{{cite web|url=http://itunes.apple.com/au/album/sos-single/id134699094|title=SOS - Single - Rihanna|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]. [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]|date=2006-04-03|accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref> In the United States, "SOS" was released on April 11, 2006, as a [[Compact Disc single|CD single]].<ref name="USRelease">{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/SOS/dp/B001144ELA/ref=sr_1_cc_1?s=music&ie=UTF8&qid=1325467133&sr=1-1-catcorr|title=Rihanna - SOS|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|date=2006-04-11|accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref> In Germany, the song was released on April 15, 2006, also as a physical maxi single.<ref name="GermanyRelease">{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.de/Sos-Rihanna/dp/B000F1ILRI/ref=sr_1_4?ie=UTF8&qid=1325466445&sr=8-4|title=Rihanna - SOS|publisher=Amazon.de|date=2006-04-15|accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref> The package consisted of the radio edit and instrumental versions of "SOS" and "Break It Off", in addition to the music video for "SOS".<ref name="GermanyRelease"/> In the United Kingdom, "SOS" was released on April 17, 2006, as a CD single.<ref name="UKRelease">{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.co.uk/SOS-Rihanna/dp/B000F5GNQU/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1325466400&sr=8-1|title=Rihanna - SOS|publisher=Amazon.co.uk|date=2006-04-17|accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref>

==Response==
===Critical reception===
Upon the release of the album, "SOS" garnered positive reviews from music critics. Bill Lamb of [[About.com]] praised the sampling of Cobb's "Tainted Love" and Rihanna's vocal performance, with specific regard to her lower register.<ref name="Top40SingleReview">{{cite web|last=Lamb|first=Bill|url=http://top40.about.com/od/singles/gr/rihannasos.htm|title=Rihanna - S.O.S. (Rescue Me) (Def Jam)|publisher=[[About.com]]. [[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref> However, Lamb criticized Rihanna for not displaying any sense of originality.<ref name="Top40SingleReview"/> Additionally, Lamb compared Rihanna's vocal performance in the song to [[Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles]], writing "The echoes of Beyonce in the higher register are weaker."<ref name="Top40SingleReview"/> Sal Cinquemani of [[Slant Magazine]] praised the sample and noted that "SOS" rivals Rihanna's debut single "[[Pon De Replay]]" (''[[Music of the Sun]]'', 2005).<ref name="Slant">{{cite news|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/rihanna-a-girl-like-me/794|title=Rihanna: A Girl Like Me|publisher=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=2006-04-24|accessdate=2010-09-11}}</ref> Despite praising "SOS", Cinquemani continued to write that it was the only song on ''A Girl Like Me'' which displayed a high level of "audacity".<ref name="Slant"/> David Jeffries of [[Allmusic]] described "SOS" as a "sexy club tune."<ref>{{cite web|last=Jeffries|first=David|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-girl-like-me-r828728/review|title=Rihanna <U+2013> A Girl Like Me|publisher=Allmusic. All Media Guide (Rovi)|accessdate=2011-12-25}}</ref>  Quentin B. Huff of Popmatters was complimentary of the song, writing, "all things considered, '[SOS]' is a decent song, brimming with energy and perfectly suited to Rihanna<U+2019>s layered vocals."<ref name="Popmatters">{{cite web|last=Huff|first=Quentin B.|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/rihanna-a-girl-like-me|title=Rihanna: A Girl Like Me|publisher=Popmatters|date=2006-06-01|accessdate=2012-01-01}}</ref>

